^D@2hondo717: kia wants to know how could he judge leading back a diamond rather than partner's suit @E@3led. It all has to do with the particular hand, and what you are trying to accomplish. Looking at dummy in the last hand, you can visualize that, if you lead a high diamond to knock out the K or Q, if aggie ever gets in and leads a second diamond, you will take 4 diamond tricks. So that is why you should lead a diamond. Later on I will discuss as to which diamond. 

Basically, there are a number of defensive rules that you should follow in general because they work on the vast majority of hands, and they also help partner figure out what you have. On defense, you need to have a plan, just like when you are declarer, and try to visualize how to defeat the contract. It is much harder to do this on defense, but you should practice visualizing defensive strategy the same way that you visualize declarer play. You do that by imagining what kind of holdings declarer and partner need to have (and can reasonably be expected to have) to beat the contract. 

On the last hand, if you think about it, it should be easy to see how you can take 4 diamond tricks if aggie has any entry at all, and at least 2 diamonds.  

Regarding what diamond to lead from kia's hand, first, let me define what an interior sequence is. It is a holding where you have a sequence headed by the J or headed by the 10, and also another higher honor. So, interior sequence holdings are AJ10, KJ10, A109, K109, or Q109 (but NOT QJ10). Originally, if you chose to lead the suit, you would lead the top of the sequence (so, J from AJ0 or 10 from Q109 for example). And many people still play that.|
