^D@2However, only on OPENING LEAD AGAINST NT, some people play what is known as "coded 10s and @E@39s". The problem they are trying to solve is for partner to figure out whether or not you have a higher honor. Using the method I just described, you would also lead J from J10 and no higher honor, and 10 from 109 and no higher honor, so partner could not tell whether or not you had a higher honor.. The solution is to play the lead of a 10 or 9 shows zero or two higher honors. So, from AJ10 or KJ10, against NT, you would lead the 10, and from A109, K109, and Q109 you would lead the 9. Note that you would also lead the 10 from 109 and the 9 from 98 with no higher honors. So, how does that help? Well, first of all, if partner leads the J, you know he has  no higher honor (some people call that "J denies"). Second, if partner leads the 10, and you can see the J, then partner can't have a higher honor (because from AJ10 or KJ10 partner would have led the 10, but since you can see the J, partner can't have that holding). Similarly, if partner leads the 9 and you can see the 10, you know partner was leading from 98 with no higher honors. Note that saying "10 or 9 shows zero or two higher honors" is correct, but insufficient. Some people mistakenly lead 10 from QJ10 (you do have two higher honors), but from that sequence you lead Q (the top of the sequence). You only lead a coded 10 or 9 from a broken sequence.

Unless you are really in love with coded 10s and 9s, I suggest you lead top of all sequences, interior or not, and forget about coded 10s and 9s for the moment. Once you get used to top of sequences, you can switch to coded 10s and 9s if you like.

On the particular hand in question, Kia was not on opening lead, so coded 10s and 9s did not apply (assuming you even played them). Since you could see the KQ in dummy, the lead of the J actually provided more information than the lead of the 10. If Kia had led the 10, you should assume he does not have the J.

